    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-03-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-03-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="268"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                <head>268. National Security Action Memorandum No. 135<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d268fn1">Source: Department of State, <gloss target="#t_NSAM1"
                            >NSAM</gloss> Files: Lot 72 D 316. Secret. Copies were sent to Attorney
                        General <persName corresp="#p_KRF1">Kennedy</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MCJA1"
                            >McCone</persName>, and General <persName corresp="#p_TMD1">Maxwell D.
                            Taylor</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-03-08">March 8, 1962</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>British Guiana</item>
                </list>
                <p>No final decision will be taken on our policy toward British Guiana and the
                        <persName>Jagan</persName> government until (a) the Secretary of State has a
                    chance to <pb facs="0584" n="552" xml:id="pg_552"/> discuss the matter with Lord
                        <persName corresp="#p_DHSAF1">Home</persName> in Geneva, and (b) <persName
                        corresp="#p_FH1">Hugh Fraser</persName> completes his on-the-spot survey in
                    British Guiana for the Colonial Office.</p>
                <p>The questions which we must answer before we reach our decision include the
                    following: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Can Great Britain be persuaded to delay independence for a
                            year?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>If Great Britain refuses to delay the date of independence, would a
                            new election before independence be possible? If so, would Jagan win or
                            lose? If he lost, what are the alternatives?</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>What are the possibilities and limitations of United States action in
                            the situation?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">John F. Kennedy</persName>
                        </hi>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d268fn2">Printed from a copy that indicates
                                <persName>Kennedy</persName> signed the original.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
